
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Responsive Design Notebook



Dimensions: --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

iPhone		: 320px by 480px





Implementing Media Queries: --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What this -- media='screen OR print' -- does is tell the browser to bring in this specific style sheet for our website
for anything that fits into this particular media.

THE ORDER OF THE STYLE SHEETS MATTERS
- the stylesheets at the bottom have the potential to override the ones at the top



Ex:

<html>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/style.css" type="text/css"> 					<- you keep your regular css file

	<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/screen.css" type="text/css" media="screen"> 	<- you add the changes to the syle.css
																					   media="screen"
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/print.css" type="text/css" media="print"> 		<- you add the print.css file when the
																						 file when the media='print'
																						(only use these if necessary)
</html>


CSS
/* Media Queries */
/*  iPhone  ----------------*/
@media screen and ( max-width: 480px )  			<- this part (max-width: 480px) is called a media feature
{ 
	s
}




@media screen and ( min-width: 1000px )
{
	s
}

What this is saying is for a viewport that is using a width GREATER THAN OR EQUAL TO 1000 pixels, use these styles.






















